  "meta": {
    "title": "Winogradsky Column: Sulfur Cycling in Estuary Mud",
    "date": "2026-07-20",
    "lesson": "A Winogradsky column recreates a stratified sediment ecosystem in a jar: light and oxygen penetrate from the top, while organic matter and sulfide accumulate near the anoxic bottom. Purple and green sulfur bacteria live at the oxic/anoxic interface, oxidizing hydrogen sulfide instead of using enzymes to break down food particles. This scenario asks you to keep a chemolithotrophic founder alive within a narrow sulfide-rich band, illustrating how redox gradients create sharply layered niches in muddy estuary sediments.",
    "citation": "Winogradsky, S. (1887) original column experiments; modern estuarine sulfur-cycling studies (e.g. Wadden Sea, San Francisco Bay mudflats).",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "realWorldBasis": "Winogradsky column / estuarine sulfureta redox stratification"
  },
